UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219969501373E
KW  - Capital mobility
KW  - Factor content of trade
KW  - Foreign investment
KW  - International factor mobility
KW  - Leontief paradox
AB  - In a world where capital is internationally mobile, care is required in interpreting data on the factor content of trade. US data for the 1960s seems to suggest that the US should have been abundantly endowed with labour relative to capital in comparison with the world as a whole. Ethier and Svensson's (1986, J. International Economics 20, pp.21–42) work on international factor mobility provides the basis for an interesting re-examination of such Leontief paradoxes. Given that the US exports capital services directly, its exports of goods would, on average, be intensive in its relatively abundant internationally immobile factors and, thus, need not be capital intensive.
